1
00:00:00,285 --> 00:00:09,543
(Q31) For my project on invertebrates, I chose to study tardigrades. These are microscopic – or to be more precise – near-microscopic animals. 在我的无脊椎动物研究项目中，我选择了研究缓步动物（tardigrades）。它们是微观生物，更准确地说，是接近微观大小的动物。（near-microscopic 不等于完全看不见，大型种类肉眼勉强可见）

2
00:00:09,543 --> 00:00:17,210
There are well over a thousand known species of these tiny animals, which belong to the phylum Tardigrada. 目前已知的这类微小动物有一千多个物种，它们属于缓步动物门（Phylum Tardigrada）。

3
00:00:17,210 --> 00:00:29,363
Most tardigrades range in length from 0.05 to 1 millimetre, though the largest species can grow to be 1.2 millimetres in length. 大多数缓步动物体长在0.05毫米到1毫米之间，不过最大的种类可以长到1.2毫米。

4
00:00:29,363 --> 00:00:38,239
[31答案句] They are also sometimes called 'water bears': 'water' because that's where they thrive best, and 'bear' because of the way they <b style="background-color: rgb(200, 230, 201);"><u>move</u></b>. 它们有时也被称为**“水熊虫（water bears）”**：之所以叫“水”，是因为它们最适宜生活在水环境中；之所以叫“熊”，则是因为它们的移动方式看起来像熊。（thrive = 茁壮生长、繁衍，而不仅仅是“生存”）

5
00:00:38,239 --> 00:00:45,737
(Q32) 'Moss piglet' is another name for tardigrades because of the way they look when viewed from the front. **“苔藓小猪（moss piglet）”**也是缓步动物的别称，因为从正面看时，它们长得有点像小猪。

6
00:00:45,737 --> 00:00:54,968
They were first discovered in Germany in 1773 by Johann Goeze, who coined the name Tardigrada. 1773年，德国学者Johann Goeze首次发现了它们，并创造了**Tardigrada（缓步动物）**这一名称。（coin a name = 创造、首次提出一个名称）

7
00:00:54,968 --> 00:01:07,520
As I say, there are many different species of tardigrade – too many to describe here – but, generally speaking, the different species share similar physical traits. 正如我刚才提到的，缓步动物的种类非常多，多到无法在这里一一介绍。不过总体来说，不同物种具有许多相似的身体特征。

8
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:16,466
[32答案句] They have a body which is <b style="background-color: rgb(200, 230, 201);"><u>short</u></b>, and also rounded – a bit like a barrel – and the body comprises four segments. 它们的身体短而圆，看起来有点像桶（barrel），并且身体由**四个体节（segments）**组成。

9
00:01:16,466 --> 00:01:23,827
(Q33) Each segment has a pair of legs, at the end of which are between four and eight sharp claws. 每个体节都有一对腿，而每条腿的末端长有4到8个锋利的爪子。

10
00:01:23,827 --> 00:01:39,638
[33 答案句] I should also say that some species don't have any claws; what they have are <span style="background-color: rgb(200, 230, 201);"><b><u>discs</u></b>, </span>and these work by means of suction. They enable the tardigrade to cling on to surfaces or to grip its prey. 我还应该补充一点，有些物种并没有爪子，而是长有吸盘状结构（discs），它们通过吸附作用发挥功能。这些结构能帮助缓步动物附着在物体表面，或者抓住猎物。（cling on to = 紧紧附着；grip prey = 抓住猎物）

11
00:01:39,638 --> 00:01:44,740
(Q34) Within the body, there are no lungs, or any organs for breathing at all. 在它们体内，没有肺，也完全没有专门负责呼吸的器官。

12
00:01:44,740 --> 00:01:52,891
[34答案句] Instead, <b><u>oxygen</u></b> and also blood are transported in a fluid that fills the cavity of the body. 相反，氧气和体液（这里可理解为血液）是在充满身体腔体的一种液体中运输的。（body cavity = 体腔）

13
00:01:52,891 --> 00:02:02,606
(Q35) As far as the tardigrade's head is concerned, the best way I can describe this is that it looks rather strange – a bit squashed even. 至于缓步动物的头部，我觉得最贴切的描述是：它看起来相当奇怪，甚至有点被压扁了（squashed）。

14
00:02:02,606 --> 00:02:10,393
Though many of the websites I looked at described its appearance as cute, which isn't exactly very scientific. 尽管我浏览过的许多网站都把它描述得很可爱，但这种说法显然不太科学。

15
00:02:10,393 --> 00:02:19,229
[35 答案句] The tardigrade's mouth is a kind of<b style="background-color: rgb(200, 230, 201);"><u> tube </u></b>that can open outwards to reveal teeth-like structures known as 'stylets'. 缓步动物的嘴巴是一种管状结构，可以向外张开，露出一种类似牙齿的结构，称为口针（stylets）。

16
00:02:19,229 --> 00:02:23,890
(Q36) These are sharp enough to pierce plant or animal cells. 这些口针十分锋利，足以刺穿植物细胞或动物细胞。（pierce = 刺穿）

17
00:02:23,890 --> 00:02:27,329
So, where are tardigrades found? 那么，缓步动物主要分布在哪里呢？

18
00:02:27,329 --> 00:02:40,181
Well, they live in every part of the world, in a variety of habitats: most commonly, on the bed of a lake, or on many kinds of plants or in very wet environments. 它们遍布世界各地，生活在各种环境中，最常见的是湖底、各种植物表面以及潮湿环境中。

19
00:02:40,181 --> 00:02:49,315
There's been some interesting research which has found that tardigrades are capable of surviving radiation and very high pressure. 有一些有趣的研究发现，缓步动物能够承受辐射以及极高的压力。

20
00:02:49,315 --> 00:03:03,149
[36答案句] And they're also able to withstand temperatures <b>as cold as –200 degrees centigrade, or highs of </b>more than 148 degrees centigrade, which is incredibly hot. 它们还能够耐受低至零下200摄氏度、高达148摄氏度以上的极端温度，这简直令人难以置信。（withstand = 承受，经受住）

21
00:03:03,149 --> 00:03:13,382
(Q37) It has been said that tardigrades could survive long after human beings have been wiped out, even in the event of an asteroid hitting the earth. 有人甚至认为，即使发生小行星撞击地球这样的灾难，在人类灭绝之后很久，缓步动物仍然能够存活。（wipe out = 彻底消灭）

22
00:03:13,382 --> 00:03:22,250
If conditions become too extreme and tardigrades are at risk of drying out, they enter a state called cryptobiosis. 如果环境变得过于恶劣，缓步动物面临脱水风险，它们就会进入一种被称为**隐生状态（cryptobiosis）**的休眠状态。

23
00:03:22,250 --> 00:03:34,502
They curl into a ball, called a tun – that's T-U-N – by retracting their head and legs, and their metabolism drops to less than one percent of normal levels. 它们会把头和腿缩回身体内，蜷缩成一个球状体，称为tun（桶状体），此时它们的新陈代谢会降到正常水平的1%以下。（retract = 缩回）

24
00:03:34,502 --> 00:03:42,480
They can remain like this until they are re-introduced to water, when they will come back to life in a matter of a few hours. 它们可以一直保持这种状态，直到重新接触到水，然后在几个小时内恢复生命活动。（in a matter of a few hours = 短短几个小时内）

25
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:50,454
[37 答案句] While in a state of cryptobiosis, tardigrades produce a protein that protects their DNA. 处于隐生状态时，缓步动物会产生一种能够保护DNA的蛋白质。

26
00:03:50,454 --> 00:03:58,243
(Q38) In 2016, scientists revived two tardigrades that had been tuns for more than 30 years. 2016年，科学家成功复活了两只已经保持桶状体状态超过30年的缓步动物。（revive = 使复活）

27
00:03:58,243 --> 00:04:08,888
There was a report that, in 1948, a 120-year-old tun was revived, but this experiment has never been repeated. 曾有报道称，1948年一只已经处于桶状体状态120年的缓步动物被成功复活，但这一实验后来从未被重复验证。（IELTS易错点：report 不等于事实，只表示“有报道声称”）

28
00:04:08,888 --> 00:04:21,584
[38答案句] There are currently several tests taking place in space, to determine how long tardigrades might be able to survive there. I believe the record so far is 10 days. 目前有多项太空实验正在进行，以确定缓步动物究竟能在太空中存活多久。据我所知，目前的纪录是10天。

29
00:04:21,584 --> 00:04:30,664
(Q39) So, erm, moving on. In terms of their diet, tardigrades consume liquids in order to survive. 接下来谈谈它们的饮食。缓步动物主要通过摄取液体来维持生存。

30
00:04:30,664 --> 00:04:34,629
Although they have teeth, they don't use these for chewing. 虽然它们有牙状结构，但并不用来咀嚼。

31
00:04:34,629 --> 00:04:46,671
[39答案句] They suck the juices from moss, or extract fluid from seaweed, but some species prey on other tardigrades, from other species or within their own. 它们会吸取苔藓中的汁液，或从海藻中提取液体。不过，有些种类会捕食其他缓步动物，包括其他物种甚至同类。（prey on = 捕食）

32
00:04:46,671 --> 00:04:55,367
(Q40) I suppose this isn't surprising, given that tardigrades are mainly comprised of liquid and are coated with a type of gel. 考虑到缓步动物主要由液体构成，并且表面覆盖着一层凝胶状物质，这一点似乎也不令人意外。（be comprised of = 由……组成）

33
00:04:55,367 --> 00:05:00,565
Finally, I'd like to mention the conservation status of tardigrades. 最后，我想谈谈缓步动物的保护现状。

34
00:05:00,565 --> 00:05:11,575
It is estimated that they have been in existence for approximately half a billion years and, in that time, they have survived five mass extinctions. 据估计，它们已经存在了大约5亿年，并且在此期间成功挺过了五次生物大灭绝。

35
00:05:11,575 --> 00:05:24,654
[40答案句] So, it will probably come as no surprise to you, that tardigrades have not been evaluated by the International Union for Conservation of Nature and are not on any<span style="background-color: rgb(200, 230, 201);"><b><u> endangered </u></b></span>list. 因此，你们大概不会感到意外：缓步动物尚未接受International Union for Conservation of Nature的保护等级评估，也不在任何濒危物种名单上。（IELTS听力易错：不是“被评为安全”，而是“根本没有评估”）

36
00:05:24,654 --> 00:05:29,216
Some researchers have described them as thriving. 一些研究人员甚至形容它们正处于繁盛发展的状态（thriving）。

37
00:05:29,216 --> 00:05:31,716
Does anyone have any questions they'd like to ask? 大家有什么想问的问题吗？

